=========================
DAY 13 — Inheritance
=========================

DEFINITION:
Inheritance allows one class to acquire properties of another class.

SYNTAX:
class Parent {}
class Child extends Parent {}

EXAMPLE:
class Vehicle {
    void run() {
        System.out.println("Vehicle running");
    }
}

class Bike extends Vehicle {
    void speed() {
        System.out.println("High speed");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Bike b = new Bike();
        b.run();
        b.speed();
    }
}

TYPES:
Single inheritance
Multilevel inheritance
Hierarchical inheritance

  MULTILEVEL EXAMPLE:
class A {
    void showA() {
        System.out.println("A");
    }
}

class B extends A {
    void showB() {
        System.out.println("B");
    }
}

class C extends B {
    void showC() {
        System.out.println("C");
    }
}

=========================
METHOD OVERLOADING
=========================
Method Overloading means multiple methods in the same class with the same name but different parameters.

Key Points:
Same method name
Different parameters (type / number / order)
Happens in same class
Compile-time polymorphism
  
Example:
class Calculator {

    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    int add(int a, int b, int c) {
        return a + b + c;
    }

    double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }
}

Why used?
Improves code readability
Same function name for similar operations
Flexibility
  
=========================
METHOD OVERRIDING
=========================
Method Overriding means child class gives its own implementation of a method already defined in parent class.

Key Points:
Same method name
Same parameters
Requires inheritance
Runtime polymorphism
  
Example:
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Animal a = new Dog();
        a.sound();
    }
}

Why used?
To change or extend parent behavior
Real-world customization

=========================
WHY MULTIPLE INHERITANCE NOT ALLOWED IN JAVA
=========================
Multiple inheritance means one class inherits from more than one class.

Java does NOT support multiple inheritance using classes.

Example:

class A {}
class B {}
class C extends A, B {} // ❌ Not allowed

REASON 1 — DIAMOND PROBLEM

If both parent classes have same method:

class A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("A");
    }
}

class B {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("B");
    }
}

Now:
If Java allowed:

class C extends A, B {
    // confusion: which show()?
}

Problem: ambiguity (confusion)

This is called Diamond Problem
  
REASON 2 — AMBIGUITY
Compiler cannot decide which parent method to call
Leads to runtime confusion
JAVA SOLUTION:

Java avoids this problem by:

Allowing single inheritance (class)
Allowing multiple inheritance using interfaces

INTERFACE SOLUTION:
interface A {
    void show();
}

interface B {
    void show();
}

class C implements A, B {
    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Resolved ambiguity");
    }
}
